<h1>Indonesia</h1>

<p>
	In February 2014, <a href="http://www.bi.go.id/en/Default.aspx">"The Bank Sentral Republik Indonesia"</a> announced that digital currencies are neither currency nor legal payment tools in Indonesia. It also advised people to stay away from Bitcoin and other virtual money. However, since then no actions have been taken against local crypto-exchanges and trading coins as well as organizing ICOs are still technically legal in this country. However, that intermediary period is not likely to exist for very long and the harsh regulatory regime will likely to be implemented in the mid-term perspectives.
</p>
<p>
	Business Notes for Startups Founders:
	<ul>		
		<li>political climate: not friendly;</li>
		<li>economic climate: moderately friendly;</li>
		<li>regions to focus: locally;</li>
		<li>industries to focus: e-jobs, FinTech, e-commerce;</li>
		<li>major limitations: fixed Internet penetration rate is around 20%, low mid-income consumers (per-capita is under $4000), high legal and administrative barriers;</li>
		<li>stimulus: still expanding economy (GDP growth rate has fallen from 6-7% in 2010 to 4-5% in 2017), large population of 260 million, fast growing mobile communication network;</li>
		<li>opportunities: to build an e-business aimed at mobile Internet users in sectors of e-jobs, FinTech and e-commerce;</li>
		<li>Cryptocurrencies and ICOs (outlook): legal (negative).</li>
	</ul>
</p>

